   <abstract >This dissertation traces the history of the Confederate Episcopal Church and its subsequent historiography to untangle the relationship between the Episcopal Church, white supremacy, and the Lost Cause. I begin in the 1850s and work to track the history and historiography of this short-lived denomination through to 1915. The Confederate Episcopal Church only existed from 1861 until 1865 but counted many Confederate leaders among its ranks and had Confederate general as one of its bishops. The bishops argued that its creation was due to political necessity, but that argument ignores the personal economic investment many in the denomination had in the protection of slavery. I employ a large source base of letters, journals, manuscripts, institutional records, and sermons to track how the Confederate bishops understood their relationship to slavery publicly and privately. I then follow how those bishops obscured those views during the Civil War and early Reconstruction. After, I investigate how later historians and biographers contributed to a Lost Cause view of this denomination through hagiographic writing and intentional editing of sources. This dissertation contends that white supremacy has always been a part of the Episcopal Church in the American South, but that it went unremarked within church histories due to a lack of critical engagement by scholars. This is a history that draws on the insights of Civil War scholarship, slavery studies, Black feminist thought, histories of Southern religion, and church history. I offer it both as a corrective to the history of the Episcopal Church in the nineteenth century American South and a case study for how church history might confront the underlying white supremacy within our scholarly roots.</abstract>
